{
  "text": "Recruitment of monocytes is one of the earliest events in initiation of atherosclerotic lesion. Disruption in processes for monocyte recruitment abrogates initiation and progression of atherosclerosis, whereas neointimal formation and plaque progression is enhanced by processes that promote macrophage infiltration. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] 22 The present studies show that AII promotes infiltration of macrophages. Thus, although 50% of the lesion in apoE\u03ea/\u03ea3 apoE\u03e9/\u03e9mice is occupied by macrophages, \u03f790% of the lesion area of apoE\u03ea/\u03ea3 apoE\u03e9/\u03e9 mice exposed to AII is macrophage-positive (Figure 2A) . These findings indicate that factors that promote accumulation of abnormal macrophages unable to secrete apoE lead to more foam cell formation and promote atherosclerotic lesions. AII enhanced monocyte infiltration into the vessel wall not only in mice reconstituted with apoE-deficient marrow but also in mice reconstituted with wild-type marrow, although in the absence of the proatherogenic macrophages, increase in atherosclerosis did not ensue. Thus, apoE\u03e9/\u03e9 3 apoE\u03e9/\u03e9 exposed to AII had significantly more macrophage-positive area than apoE\u03e9/\u03e9 3 apoE\u03e9/\u03e9 mice infused with saline. Because oil-red-O staining was similar between these 2 groups of mice, it is possible that more of the lipids were contained within the macrophages. The association between AII and macrophage infiltration has been made in other circumstances, including renal fibrosis and in ischemic heart disease. [CITATION_4] 24 The potentially injurious effect of AII has been linked to augmentation of inflammatory cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor-\u2423, IL-6, and chemokines such as MCP-1/CCR2 in the arterial wall, kidney, and heart. We and others have shown the pivotal effect of AII on MCP-1 and CCR2 in atherogenesis such that AII increases while antagonism of AII lessens their gene expression and immunostaining. [CITATION_5] 25 These observations support the possibility that AII stimulation of MCP-1 is an early proatherogenic factor. However, there is less known about the effects of AII on monocyte/macrophage function in atherogenesis. Our data show that AII affects cholesterol efflux in intact macrophages but not in apoE\u03ea/\u03ea cells. The net result of this cholesterol efflux in vivo remains to be determined.",
  "citation_candidates": [
